[[File:HMCS Miramichi MIKAN 4821368.jpg|thumb|upright|''Miramichi'' between 1957 and 1965]]
'''HMCS ''Miramichi''''' ([[Hull classification symbol (Canada)|hull number]] MCB 163) was a {{sclass2-|Bay|minesweeper}} that was constructed for the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] during the [[Cold War]]. Entering service in 1957, the vessel was used as a [[training ship]] on the [[British Columbia Coast|West Coast of Canada]] for the majority of her career. ''Mirmaichi'' was [[Ship decommissioning|decommissioned]] in 1998 and the vessel's fate is unknown.

==Design and description==
The Bay class were designed and ordered as replacements for the [[Second World War]]-era minesweepers that the Royal Canadian Navy operated at the time. Similar to the {{sclass2-|Ton|minesweeper|1}}, they were constructed of wood planking and aluminum framing.<ref name=m1>Macpherson and Barrie, p. 271</ref><ref name=con1>Gardiner and Chumbley, p. 49</ref>

[[Displacement (ship)|Displacing]] {{convert|390|LT|t}} standard at {{convert|412|LT|t}} at deep load, the minesweepers were {{convert|152|ft|m|abbr=on}} [[Length overall|long]] with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|28|ft|m|abbr=on}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|8|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=m1/><ref name=con1/> They had a complement of 38 officers and ratings.<ref name=m1/><ref group=note>Gardiner and Chumbley claim the complement was 40.</ref>

The Bay-class minesweepers were powered by two [[General Motors|GM]] 12-cylinder [[diesel engine]]s driving two shafts creating {{convert|2400|bhp|lk=in}}. This gave the ships a maximum speed of {{convert|16|kn|lk=in}} and a range of {{convert|3290|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn}}.<ref name=con1/><ref name=j1>Moore, p. 82</ref> The ships were armed with one [[40 mm Bofors]] gun and were equipped with minesweeping gear.<ref name=m1/><ref name=con1/>

==Operational history==
Ordered as a replacement for [[sister ship]], {{HMCS|Miramichi|MCB 150|3}} which had been transferred to the [[French Navy]] in 1954, the ship's [[keel]] was laid down on 2 February 1956 by [[Victoria Machinery Depot]] at their yard in [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]]. Named for a [[Miramichi Bay|bay]] located in [[New Brunswick]], ''Miramichi'' was [[Ship naming and launching|launched]] on 22 February 1957. The ship was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 29 October 1957.<ref name=mac275>Macpherson and Barrie, p. 275</ref>

After commissioning, the minesweeper joined Training Group Pacific on the [[British Columbia Coast|West Coast of Canada]].<ref name=mac275/> In 1972, the class was redesignated patrol escorts.<ref name=m1/> The vessel remained a part of the unit until being [[Ship decommissioning|paid off]] on 16 December 1998.<ref name=mac275/> Colledge claims the vessel was paid off in October 1998.<ref>Colledge, p. 414</ref>

